comments.body:
Hi @jwbay thanks for the review.

Honestly, I'm not sure why this works (which is not a good sign), but it does. My original approach unioned a no-arg, 1-arg, and 2-arg component class (to handle exactly what you point out), but I dropped that approach when I realized this simpler approach actually does work.

E.g. if I change `MyComponent` and `AnotherComponent` to have 0-arg constructors:

```
class MyComponent extends Component<MyComponentProps, MyComponentState> {
    constructor() {
        super({stringProp: "1", numberProp: 2});
    }
    setState(...args: any[]) {
        console.log(args);
    }
}

class AnotherComponent extends Component<AnotherComponentProps> {
    constructor() {
        super({});
    }
    setState(...args: any[]) {
        console.log(args);
    }
}
```

All of the enyzme-tests code still type-checks, including this line that is in this PR:

```
        const s1: EnzymeComponentClass<AnotherComponentProps> = AnotherComponent;
```

Oh...actually, I bet I know why it works; in TS it's legal to implement a method but not declare all of the parameters, e.g.:

```
type Callback = (status: number, done: boolean) => void;
function doSomething(c: Callback) {}
doSomething(() => console.log("done"));
```

The 0-arg closure still matches the 2-arg `Callback` type, by conveniently ignoring the two params.

So, in the same way, a 0-arg `MyComponent.new()` will (somewhat surprisingly but actually conveniently) match the `ComponentClass.new(props, context)` and so the `find<P2>(component: ComponentClass<P2>): ShallowWrapper<P2, any>` overload still kicks in.

